<p:sld xmlns:a="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/drawingml/2006/main" xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships" xmlns:p="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/presentationml/2006/main"><p:cSld><p:spTree><p:nvGrpSpPr><p:cNvPr id="1" name=""/><p:cNvGrpSpPr/><p:nvPr/></p:nvGrpSpPr><p:grpSpPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="0" y="0"/><a:ext cx="0" cy="0"/><a:chOff x="0" y="0"/><a:chExt cx="0" cy="0"/></a:xfrm></p:grpSpPr><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="2" name="Title 1"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{729EBEBB-C77E-DC67-916B-0915F8894A8B}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph type="title"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>You will be writing a technical report as part of your group project for this class</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="3" name="Content Placeholder 2"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{532405D0-3573-CF8A-E569-B204F0F96F45}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph idx="1"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>In the GitHub repository, under this week’s folder, I have set up a Markdown file with the same format for the technical report with some additional Markdown placeholders for you.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>For your group project, </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"><a:solidFill><a:srgbClr val="0E9ED5"/></a:solidFill></a:rPr><a:t>the technical report must be submitted in Markdown</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t> – so take the time to learn how to write in Markdown if you are not familiar.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>There is </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"/><a:t>a maximum word count of 3000 words </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>– you must learn to </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" err="1"/><a:t>prioritise</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t> the most critical content. Feel free to use charts or tables to illustrate your point. The only restriction is that you must write in clear prose.</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp></p:spTree><p:extLst><p:ext uri="{BB962C8B-B14F-4D97-AF65-F5344CB8AC3E}"><p14:creationId xmlns:p14="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2010/main" val="2715233168"/></p:ext></p:extLst></p:cSld><p:clrMapOvr><a:masterClrMapping/></p:clrMapOvr></p:sld>